In an affidavit they have filed before Mombasa court while seeking to detain Mr Kivatsi, ATPU officers say as they are currently undertaking a thorough investigations into three gadgets recovered from him.  The suspect was arrested on March 11, in Shimanzi Mombasa at around 7:21pm. 






“The investigations require phone details of all the persons that he has been communicating with, both in Kenya and outside, their digital prints trail(forensic investigations of their mobile phones ), and it is important for him to detained by ATPU to enable detailed criminal inquiries to be carried out,” said police constable Cohen Nyamweya. 

At the time of his arrest, police recovered two mobile phones-Samsung and Tecno- which they allege have articles believed to be used in radicalization and likely to instigate a terrorist act. ATPU arrested the suspect in collaboration with other security agencies within Mombasa, who launched investigations after receiving a tip off. 

State Counsel Ogega Bosibori, while relying on documents produced by ATPU, said that the anti-terror wing has received credible intelligence report that Mr Kivatsi is involved in recruitment of persons to participate in terrorism activities, including joining terror groups. 



